Here are some important facts about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Cèlebes:
Palu is the capital of the province of Cèlebes Central, located at the end of a narrow bay on the western coast of the island of Cèlebes, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a regency that extends along more than 300 km of coastline to the northwest of Cèlebes Island.
The regency, an administrative region below a province, had a population of approximately 299,200 in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture are the mainstays of the economy of the province of Cèlebes Central, especially in the Donggala coastal region.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but is concentrated mainly in Morowali, on the coast of the other end of Cèlebes.
Palu and Donggala have suffered several tsunamis in the past 100 years, according to Indonesia's disaster mitigation agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
In 1996, a tsunami also struck west of Donggala, killing nine people.
Indonesia is in the Pacific Ring of Fire and is frequently hit by earthquakes.
The following are the main earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: On December 26, a major earthquake on the western coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh, north of Sumatra, caused a tsunami that affected 14 countries and killed 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the western coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Thousands of people died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake struck southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, and caused a tsunami that devastated the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake shook a populated area of Padang City, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake shook one of the Mentawai Islands off the coast of Sumatra, and caused a 10-meter-high tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A mild earthquake affected the Pidie Jaya Regency in Aceh and caused destruction and panic, as the population recalled the devastation of the 2004 earthquake and deadly tsunami.
