Red tide update: concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in certain parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more dispersed proliferation conditions are being reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting a lower concentration.
Red tide proliferation extends along approximately 200 km of coastline, from Pinellas north to Lee counties south.
Spots can be found 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places, compared to last week's situation.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium coastal or offshore concentrations in Pinellas County have been reported over the past week, low-to-high coastal concentrations in Hillsborough County, bottom-to-high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom-to-medium concentrations in Charlotte County, bottom-to-high coastal or offshore concentrations in Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritations continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported over the past week in northeast Florida.
